# Game Models Implementation Guidelines

## GameUnit Model
The `GameUnit` class should:
- Store color and shape properties
- Track position on the board
- Maintain selection state
- Support serialization for save/load functionality
- Include methods for checking match compatibility

Example implementation pattern:
```dart
class GameUnit {
  final String color;
  final String shape;
  final Position position;
  bool isSelected;
  
  // Constructor
  GameUnit({
    required this.color,
    required this.shape,
    required this.position,
    this.isSelected = false,
  });
  
  // Check if this unit matches another by color
  bool matchesColorWith(GameUnit other) => this.color == other.color;
  
  // Check if this unit matches another by shape
  bool matchesShapeWith(GameUnit other) => this.shape == other.shape;
  
  // Check if this is a perfect match (both color and shape)
  bool isPerfectMatchWith(GameUnit other) => 
      matchesColorWith(other) && matchesShapeWith(other);
      
  // Clone with new properties
  GameUnit copyWith({
    String? color,
    String? shape,
    Position? position,
    bool? isSelected,
  }) {
    return GameUnit(
      color: color ?? this.color,
      shape: shape ?? this.shape,
      position: position ?? this.position,
      isSelected: isSelected ?? this.isSelected,
    );
  }
}
```

## Level Model
The `Level` class should:
- Define level configuration and objectives
- Store the initial board state
- Track progress and completion status
- Include methods for checking win conditions

## Achievement Model
The `Achievement` class should:
- Define achievement criteria and rewards
- Track progress toward completion
- Include methods for checking if conditions are met

## PlayerStats Model
The `PlayerStats` class should:
- Track all player statistics
- Support persistence between sessions
- Include methods for updating stats based on gameplay